The topic here started is full of matter for curious and interesting investigation ε whether on the one hand we suppose that several ingenious arm, being already introduced into Rome in the persons of slaves, would only very slowly be admitted as objects of liberal pursuit 3 or reflect, on the other hand, that the system of clientela, however well it might work in an earlier stage of the commonwealth, at a later period could only tend to keep the clientes too proud to gain what we should call an honest and reputable livelihood, so long as they were able barely to live on the allowance made by the patroni. Hence the pride of caste was maintained, but at the eost of all manly independence: and in the client whom Juvenal describes thus subsisting as the poor gentle- man of his day, we see the miserable wreck of Roman freedom, and of all the higher virtues by which it was once

adorned.
